@section standard_app_entry Application Entry Point

<b>Files:</b> `main.c`, `main_std_app.h`

Provides the `main()` entry point (placed in `.boot`). On startup it detects
the launch mode:
- <b>Standalone</b> (`arg0 == 0`):<br>
  Calls `standalone_app_main()` → `common_app_init()` → `app_main()`.

- <b>Exchange library</b> (`arg0 != 0`, requires `HAVE_SWAP`):<br>
  Calls `library_app_main()` which dispatches `SIGN_TRANSACTION`, `CHECK_ADDRESS`, or `GET_PRINTABLE_AMOUNT` to the coin-application callbacks.

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref app_exit() "app_exit()" | Stops I/O and returns to the dashboard via `os_sched_exit(-1)`. Declared `noreturn`. |
| @ref common_app_init() "common_app_init()" | Initialises UX, seproxyhal I/O, and — when `HAVE_APP_STORAGE` is defined — NVM storage. |
| @ref standalone_app_main() "standalone_app_main()" | Default standalone entry; resets swap globals, calls `common_app_init()` then `app_main()`. |
| @ref library_app_main() "library_app_main()" | Exchange library dispatcher (requires `HAVE_SWAP`). |

@note All four are `WEAK` and may be overridden by the application.

<br>

---

@section standard_app_io I/O Layer

<b>Files:</b> `io.h`, `io.c`

A portable APDU I/O layer on top of seproxyhal.<br>The typical receive/dispatch
loop in `app_main()` looks like:

@code{.c}
void app_main(void) {
    io_init();
    for (;;) {
        int len = io_recv_command();
        if (len < 0) break;
        // parse and handle the APDU stored in G_io_apdu_buffer …
        io_send_sw(SW_OK);
    }
}
@endcode

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref io_init() "io_init()" | Arms the deferred I/O start; must be called once before the first @ref io_recv_command(). |
| @ref io_recv_command() "io_recv_command()" | Blocks until a full APDU is received into `G_io_apdu_buffer`; returns byte count or -1. |
| @ref io_send_response_buffers() "io_send_response_buffers(rdatalist, count, sw)" | Assembles a response from an array of `buffer_t` fragments, appends `sw`, and transmits. |
| @ref io_send_response_pointer() "io_send_response_pointer(ptr, size, sw)" | Convenience wrapper for a raw pointer. |
| @ref io_send_response_buffer() "io_send_response_buffer(rdata, sw)" | Convenience wrapper for a single `buffer_t`. |
| @ref io_send_sw() "io_send_sw(sw)" | Sends a status-word-only response (no data). |
| @ref app_ticker_event_callback() "app_ticker_event_callback()" | Empty `WEAK` hook called on each ticker event; override to receive periodic ticks. |

@note When `HAVE_SWAP` is active and `G_swap_response_ready == true`,
`io_send_response_buffers()` signals Exchange and calls `os_lib_end()` instead
of returning normally.

<br>

---

@section standard_app_parser APDU Parser

<b>Files:</b> `parser.h`, `parser.c`

Parses a raw APDU byte buffer into a structured `command_t`:

@code{.c}
typedef struct {
    uint8_t  cla;   ///< Instruction class
    uint8_t  ins;   ///< Instruction code
    uint8_t  p1;    ///< Parameter 1
    uint8_t  p2;    ///< Parameter 2
    uint8_t  lc;    ///< Command data length (0 when absent)
    uint8_t *data;  ///< Pointer into the original buffer; NULL when lc == 0
} command_t;
@endcode

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref apdu_parser() "apdu_parser(cmd, buf, buf_len)" | Fills `cmd` from `buf`. Returns `false` if the buffer is too short or the declared `Lc` doesn't match the actual remaining bytes. |

Byte-offset constants (`OFFSET_CLA = 0`, `OFFSET_INS = 1`, … `OFFSET_CDATA = 5`) are
defined in `offsets.h`.

<br>

---

@section standard_app_buffer Buffer Abstraction

<b>Files:</b> `buffer.h`, `buffer.c`

A cursor-based byte-buffer API. All operations advance (or set) the internal
`offset` field and return `false` on a bounds violation.

@code{.c}
typedef struct {
    uint8_t *ptr;
    size_t   size;
    size_t   offset;  ///< read/write cursor
} buffer_t;

// Quick construction
buffer_t b = buffer_create(my_array, sizeof(my_array));
@endcode

<b>Reading</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref buffer_can_read() "buffer_can_read(b, n)" | Returns `true` if at least `n` unread bytes remain. |
| @ref buffer_read_u8() "buffer_read_u8/u16/u32/u64(b, val, endianness)" | Reads 1/2/4/8 bytes and advances the cursor. `endianness` is `BE` or `LE`. |
| @ref buffer_read_varint() "buffer_read_varint(b, val)" | Reads a Bitcoin-style variable-length integer. |
| @ref buffer_read_bip32_path() "buffer_read_bip32_path(b, out, out_len)" | Reads `out_len` big-endian 32-bit BIP32 path components. |
| @ref buffer_get_path_bip32() "buffer_get_path_bip32(b, path)" | Reads a length-prefixed BIP32 path into a `path_bip32_t`. |
| @ref buffer_read_bytes() "buffer_read_bytes(b, out, n)" | Reads `n` raw bytes. |
| @ref buffer_peek() "buffer_peek(b, val)" | Reads the next byte without advancing. |
| @ref buffer_peek_n() "buffer_peek_n(b, n, val)" | Reads byte at `offset+n` without advancing. |

<b>Writing</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref buffer_write_u8() "buffer_write_u8/u16/u32/u64(b, val, endianness)" | Writes 1/2/4/8 bytes and advances. |
| @ref buffer_write_bytes() "buffer_write_bytes(b, data, n)" | Writes `n` raw bytes and advances. |

<b>Cursor control</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref buffer_seek_set() "buffer_seek_set(b, offset)" | Seeks to an absolute position. |
| @ref buffer_seek_cur() "buffer_seek_cur(b, offset)" | Advances the cursor by `offset` bytes. |
| @ref buffer_seek_end() "buffer_seek_end(b, offset)" | Sets the cursor to `size - offset`. |
| @ref buffer_get_cur() "buffer_get_cur(b)" | Returns a pointer to the current position. |

<b>Output</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref buffer_copy() "buffer_copy(b, out, out_len)" | Copies remaining bytes to `out` without advancing (used for APDU TX). Requires `size - offset <= out_len`. |
| @ref buffer_move() "buffer_move(b, out, out_len)" | Copies remaining bytes and advances by `out_len`. |

<br>

---

@section standard_app_bip32 BIP32 Path

<b>Files:</b> `bip32.h`, `bip32.c`

Parsing, serialisation, and formatting of BIP32 derivation paths.

@code{.c}
typedef struct {
    uint8_t  length;                  ///< Number of path components
    uint32_t path[MAX_BIP32_PATH];    ///< Raw path components (hardened bit included)
} path_bip32_t;
@endcode

`MAX_BIP32_PATH` is 10. The hardened-child bit mask is `BIP32_HARDENED_MASK` (`0x80000000`).

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref bip32_path_read() "bip32_path_read(in, in_len, out, out_len)" | Deserialises `out_len` big-endian 32-bit components from `in`. |
| @ref bip32_path_format() "bip32_path_format(path, len, out, out_len)" | Formats the path as `"0'/1/2'"` (hardened components get a trailing `'`). |
| @ref bip32_path_format_simple() "bip32_path_format_simple(bip32, out, out_len)" | Convenience wrapper for `path_bip32_t`. |

<br>

---

@section standard_app_crypto Cryptographic Helpers

<b>Files:</b> `crypto_helpers.h`, `crypto_helpers.c`

High-level wrappers that combine BIP32 key derivation with cryptographic
operations. Every function:
- Returns a `cx_err_t` and is annotated `WARN_UNUSED_RESULT`,
- Scrubs sensitive material with `explicit_bzero` on both success and failure,
- Only supports curves with 32-byte domain parameters (secp256k1, secp256r1, …).

<b>Key derivation</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref bip32_derive_init_privkey_256() "bip32_derive_init_privkey_256(curve, path, path_len, privkey, chain_code)" | Derives and initialises an ECFP private key. |
| @ref bip32_derive_get_pubkey_256() "bip32_derive_get_pubkey_256(curve, path, path_len, raw_pubkey, chain_code, hashID)" | Derives the private key and generates the uncompressed 65-byte public key. |

<b>ECDSA signing</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref bip32_derive_ecdsa_sign_hash_256() "bip32_derive_ecdsa_sign_hash_256(curve, path, path_len, sign_mode, hashID, hash, hash_len, sig, sig_len, info)" | Signs a pre-computed hash; output is DER-encoded (`30‖L‖02‖Lr‖r‖02‖Ls‖s`). |
| @ref bip32_derive_ecdsa_sign_rs_hash_256() "bip32_derive_ecdsa_sign_rs_hash_256(curve, path, path_len, sign_mode, hashID, hash, hash_len, r, s)" | Like above but writes raw `r` and `s` into separate 32-byte buffers. |

<b>EdDSA signing</b>

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref bip32_derive_eddsa_sign_hash_256() "bip32_derive_eddsa_sign_hash_256(curve, path, path_len, hashID, hash, hash_len, sig, sig_len)" | Signs with EdDSA; `sig_len` is updated to `domain_param_size * 2`. |

Each function has a `_with_seed_` variant that accepts a custom `seed`/`seed_len` for non-standard SLIP-21 derivations.<br>
Pass `NULL, 0` to use the standard BIP32 device seed.

<br>

---

@section standard_app_format Formatting Utilities

<b>Files:</b> `format.h`, `format.c`

Human-readable string formatting for display on device screens.

| Function | Description |
|---|---|
| @ref format_i64() "format_i64(dst, dst_len, value)" | Formats a signed 64-bit integer as decimal. |
| @ref format_u64() "format_u64(dst, dst_len, value)" | Formats an unsigned 64-bit integer as decimal. |
| @ref format_fpu64() "format_fpu64(dst, dst_len, value, decimals)" | Fixed-point decimal with `decimals` fractional digits (e.g. `12345` with `decimals=2` → `"123.45"`). |
| @ref format_fpu64_trimmed() "format_fpu64_trimmed(dst, dst_len, value, decimals)" | Like @ref format_fpu64() but trims trailing zeros and the decimal point. |
| @ref format_hex() "format_hex(in, in_len, out, out_len)" | Uppercase hex dump; requires `out_len >= 2*in_len+1`. Returns bytes written or -1. |

<br>

